      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The history of unions in the US began with the early 19th-century labor movements, which were largely driven by the Industrial Revolution and the exploitation of workers. The Knights of Labor, formed in 1869, was one of the first national labor organizations, and the American Federation of Labor (AFL), founded in 1886, played a significant role in shaping the modern labor movement. The passage of the National Labor Relations Act (NLRA) in 1935, led by President Franklin D. Roosevelt, marked a major turning point, establishing the right to collective bargaining and setting the stage for the growth of unions in the mid-20th century. Today, unions continue to play a vital role in advocating for workers' rights, with the AFL-CIO, a federation of labor unions, representing over 12 million workers across the US.",
